    <name>
				<text>37.1.5.2 Factory machines</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
A factory has \({@ma@}\) machines. \(2\) of these have been given an experimental modification. In the first week after this modification, problems are reported with \({@de@}\) of the machines. <br><br>How many different ways can we select \({@de@}\) machines from the \({@ma@}\) machines in the factory?<br><br>[[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]<br><br>Of the machines that did not have the experimental modification, how many ways could we have the observed number of problematic machines if both of the modified machines had a problem?<br><br>[[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]]<br><br>Using the above values or otherwise, what is the probability that both of the modified machines are among the \({@de@}\) with problems assuming that all machines are equally likely to give problems?<p></p><p><b>Write your answer as a rational number (fraction).</b></p>
<p>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</p>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<h4 class="HELM_solution">Solution</h4><br>There are \(\binom{{@ma@}}{{@de@}} = {@ta2@}\) possible different selections of \({@de@}\) machines in the factory. <br><br>There are \({@ma@}-2 = {@nm@}\) machines in the factory that did not have the experimental modification. Also, if both of the modified machines had a problem then \({@de@}-2 = {@fau@}\) of the remaining problematic machines did not have the modification. This means that there are \(\binom{{@nm@}}{{@fau@}} = {@ta3@}\) different ways of having this combination.<br><br>Side note: if both of the machines with the experimental modification are problematic, then there is only \(\binom{2}{2} = 1\) way of having this combination.<br><br>This means that the probability of&nbsp;that both of the modified machines are among the \({@de@}\) with problems is:\[
\dfrac{\binom{2}{2}\binom{{@nm@}}{{@fau@}}}{\binom{{@ma@}}{{@de@}}} = \dfrac{{@de@}\times{@de1@}}{{@ma@}\times{@ma1@}} = {@ta1@}
\]<br>Remark: This is an example of <em>sampling without replacement </em>which we can model using the hypermetric probability distribution.<br><br><br>Alternatively, let \( S \) be the event ``first modified machine is in the group 
of \({@de@}\)'' and \( C \) be the 
event ``second modified machine is in the group of \({@de@}\)''. Then the required probability is \[\text{P}(S)\times\text{P}(C \mid S) = \dfrac{{@de@}}{{@ma@}} \times \dfrac{{@de@}-1}{{@ma@}-1} = {@ta1@}\]]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
